dspace-development.title: Help Christa with out of band thesis submission

comments.body:
This was triggered by a maintenance-related upgrade to the server environment earlier:

```bash
pulsys   pts/2        tmux(51785).%1   Tue Oct 31 13:18   still logged in
pulsys   pts/1        tmux(51785).%0   Tue Oct 31 13:18   still logged in
pulsys   pts/0        [...]       Tue Oct 31 13:18   still logged in
reboot   system boot  [...] Tue Oct 31 08:25   still running
pulsys   pts/0        [...]       Tue Oct 31 08:20 - 08:24  (00:03)
```

I am currently trying to identify why `tomcat` was not restarted following the reboot.

It appears that the `apache-tomcat` service, which was set to the runlevels required to automatically start during the booting of the server, was in conflict with a similar service `dspace`. The former has been disabled, while the latter has been explicitly enabled:

```bash
$ sudo systemctl disable apache-tomcat.service
$ sudo systemctl enable dspace.service
```

I am applying these changes to the `staging` and `dev` environments.
While testing the `staging` environment, I am seeing that the NGINX proxy is returning a 403 status, while invoking `curl` for the localhost returns a `200`.

When requesting from the load balancer `pul-gcdc-staging-adc`, a 200 response is provided from the `staging` server, however, the reverse proxy is still returning a 403 when attempting to access https://oar-staging.princeton.edu
`/etc/nginx/conf.d/templates/restrict.conf` needed to be updated with the proper IP address range for the GlobalProtect VPN endpoints.

figgy.title: Look into Performance for CDL items whose Login prompt seems delayed/not working in Orangelight

comments.body:
I ran the network tab on the contents of the iframe that's loaded into the catalog. The examples given in the orangelight ticket took about 6 seconds to load for me. I also looked at honeybadger and didn't see any relevant errors. 

I looked at some APM and in particular at the ViewerController#auth action. It was averaging about 4 seconds, so that seems like a significant portion of the response time. I dug into the bibdata call that's part of that action, and it is just really variable. Sometimes it takes a very long time. Here's the page I was looking at: https://app.datadoghq.com/apm/resource/bibdata/rack.request/2f00923e58bd333e?query=env%3Aproduction%20service%3Abibdata%20operation_name%3Arack.request&env=production&topGraphs=latency%3Alatency%2Chits%3Acount%2Cerrors%3Acount%2CbreakdownAs%3Apercentage&traces=qson%3A%28data%3A%28%29%2Cversion%3A%210%29&start=1698175628064&end=1698780428064&paused=true

It's curious to me that the examples given in the ticket as ones where it took a long time are not examples with a lot of holdings in the bibdata items response.

Looking at a few of the bibdata traces, the ones that took the longest were the ones with lots of items.

It would be helpful to be able to replicate this more reliably :(

Here are some potentially useful docs: 
- https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/main/docs/technical/viewer-flow.md
- https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/pull/5483/files
